<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="207" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="12.[166,1226,1114,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
D i a g n o s i s. This species can be recognized among other 
<taxonomicName box="[916,1158,1249,1276]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[916,1068,1249,1275]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Campylocera</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
from the long pedicel and flagellomere 1 parallel-sided, apically bluntly rounded, fore femur with moderately long and thin setae, but without thickened apicoventral setae on dorsal surface, mid coxa with row of strong setae (
<figureCitation box="[702,780,1345,1372]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[174,207,1339,1361]" captionTargetBox="[303,1111,182,1300]" captionTargetId="figure-134@13.[298,1112,174,1300]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 14. Campylocera angustipalpis: holotype ♀ (MNKB): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, left; 4 — same, anterior; 5 — same, dorsal view; 6 —mesonotum, dorsal view; 7 — prosternum and fore coxae; 8 — fore leg, posterior view; 9 — mid femur, anterior; 10 — mid coxa; 11 — hind femur, anterior view; 12 — hind coxae; 13 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 14 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453730/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">fig. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[795,823,1345,1371]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[166,199,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[255,1063,1151,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[246,1073,1138,1759]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 10. Campylocera latigenis: holotype Ơ (NHMW): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, right; 4 — head, dorsal view; 5 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453716" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453716/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[795,823,1345,1371]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">10</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
) hind coxa antero-ventrally with somewhat thickened spinulose setulae (
<figureCitation box="[629,704,1377,1404]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[174,207,1339,1361]" captionTargetBox="[303,1111,182,1300]" captionTargetId="figure-134@13.[298,1112,174,1300]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 14. Campylocera angustipalpis: holotype ♀ (MNKB): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, left; 4 — same, anterior; 5 — same, dorsal view; 6 —mesonotum, dorsal view; 7 — prosternum and fore coxae; 8 — fore leg, posterior view; 9 — mid femur, anterior; 10 — mid coxa; 11 — hind femur, anterior view; 12 — hind coxae; 13 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 14 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453730/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">fig. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[716,744,1377,1403]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="10.[166,199,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[255,1063,1151,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-429@10.[246,1073,1138,1759]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Fig. 10. Campylocera latigenis: holotype Ơ (NHMW): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, right; 4 — head, dorsal view; 5 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453716" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453716/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[716,744,1377,1403]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">10</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
) not forming comb or thick brush; veins brown bordered, cell R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[441,468,1428,1442]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2+3</subScript>
apically with narrow brown apical margin (
<figureCitation box="[995,1071,1409,1436]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[174,207,1339,1361]" captionTargetBox="[303,1111,182,1300]" captionTargetId="figure-134@13.[298,1112,174,1300]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 14. Campylocera angustipalpis: holotype ♀ (MNKB): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, left; 4 — same, anterior; 5 — same, dorsal view; 6 —mesonotum, dorsal view; 7 — prosternum and fore coxae; 8 — fore leg, posterior view; 9 — mid femur, anterior; 10 — mid coxa; 11 — hind femur, anterior view; 12 — hind coxae; 13 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 14 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453730/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">fig. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1085,1099,1409,1435]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1748,1770]" captionTargetBox="[272,1113,774,1706]" captionTargetId="figure-10@3.[272,1122,774,1719]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 2. Campylocera ferruginea: holotype ♀ of Campylocera omissa (NHMW): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — head, left (arrow indicates enlarged setae); 3 — head, anterior view; 4 —wing; 5 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 6 — fore leg, posterior view (arrow indicates long setae); 7 — mid leg, anterior; 8 — hind leg, anterior view; 9–10 — oviscape, dorsal and left view; 11 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453690" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453690/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[1085,1099,1409,1435]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
), oviscape long and narrow, without peculiar modified structures (
<figureCitation box="[818,893,1441,1468]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="13.[174,207,1339,1361]" captionTargetBox="[303,1111,182,1300]" captionTargetId="figure-134@13.[298,1112,174,1300]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Fig. 14. Campylocera angustipalpis: holotype ♀ (MNKB): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, left; 4 — same, anterior; 5 — same, dorsal view; 6 —mesonotum, dorsal view; 7 — prosternum and fore coxae; 8 — fore leg, posterior view; 9 — mid femur, anterior; 10 — mid coxa; 11 — hind femur, anterior view; 12 — hind coxae; 13 — oviscape apex, ventrally; 14 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453730" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453730/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">fig. 14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[904,918,1441,1467]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,680,702]" captionTargetBox="[280,1119,174,659]" captionTargetId="figure-6@3.[272,1122,174,674]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. Campylocera ferruginea, holotype (MHNP): 1 — habitus, lateral view; 2 — wing; 3 — head, left (arrow indicates enlarged setae); 4 — head, anterior view; 5 — mesonotum, dorsal view; 6 — labels." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453688" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453688/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[904,918,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">1</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[931,959,1441,1467]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[166,199,563,585]" captionTargetBox="[364,1037,174,533]" captionTargetId="figure-541@12.[342,1049,167,562]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 13. Campylocera latigenis: holotype ♀ Dicrostyra partitigena (NHMW): 1 — abdomen, ventral; 2 — oviscape, right; 3 — apex of oviscape, right, enlarged; 4 — aculeus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6453728" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6453728/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
<emphasis box="[931,959,1441,1467]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">13</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
). Mesonotum without presutural supra-alar setae; scutellum short setulose, 2 setae on each side. Th is species is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hendel 1914" authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[369,638,1505,1532]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[369,388,1505,1531]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[401,483,1505,1531]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">gracilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Hendel, F." box="[489,638,1505,1532]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" pagination="77 - 117" refId="ref11510" refString="Hendel, F. 1914. Neue Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Pyrgotinen. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, 79 A (11) (1913), 77 - 117 + 1 Taf." type="journal article" year="1914">Hendel 1914</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from Southern 
<collectingCountry box="[825,912,1505,1532]" name="Nigeria" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Nigeria</collectingCountry>
differing mainly by longer setulose fore femur (short setulose with short, slightly thickened setulae apicoventrally in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[166,280,1569,1596]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[166,185,1569,1595]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[198,280,1569,1595]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Study of additional material is necessary to clarify, if this is a reliable difference of species or individual variability. No reliable associations with males found in collections are available.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="208" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="12.[166,1226,1114,1852]" lastBlockId="13.[174,1233,1481,1810]" lastPageId="13" lastPageNumber="208" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">
R e m a r k. 
<bibRefCitation author="Enderlein, G." box="[354,555,1665,1692]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" pagination="98 - 134" refId="ref11407" refString="Enderlein, G. 1942. Klassifikation der Pyrgotiden. Sitzungsberichte der Gesellschaft Naturforschenden Freunde zu Berlin, (1941) (2), 98 - 134." type="journal article" year="1942">Enderlein (1942)</bibRefCitation>
originally recognized 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1942" box="[827,938,1665,1691]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Clemaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[827,938,1665,1691]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Clemaxia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a genus to place the flies with incomplete costa, vein M reaching wing margin, R 
<subScript attach="left" box="[866,892,1716,1730]" fontSize="6" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">2+3</subScript>
with or without stump vein, and scutellum bearing 4 setae. In this paper, all the Old World 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rondani" authorityYear="1869" box="[936,1071,1729,1756]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="196" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subTribe" subTribe="Adapsiliina">Adapsiliina</taxonomicName>
species with incomplete costa are lumped in a monophyletic genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1843" box="[792,944,1761,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[792,944,1761,1787]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Campylocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. I therefore synonymize both generic names. Within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Macquart" authorityYear="1843" box="[505,657,1793,1819]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[505,657,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">Campylocera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1942" box="[672,858,1793,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Clemaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustipalpis">
<emphasis box="[672,691,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[705,858,1793,1819]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">angustipalpis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms a small group of species together with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hendel, 1908)" baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1908" box="[337,625,1825,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Hypotyphla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loewi">
<emphasis box="[337,356,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[373,433,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">loewi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hendel, F." box="[451,616,1825,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" pagination="145 - 153" refId="ref11436" refString="Hendel, F. 1908. Acht neue Pyrgotinen (Dipt.). Wiener Entomologische Zeitung, 27 (4 - 5), 145 - 153." type="journal article" year="1908">Hendel, 1908</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[640,757,1825,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[640,659,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[675,757,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Hendel, 1914)" baseAuthorityName="Hendel" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[828,1149,1825,1852]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Hypotyphla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="caudata">
<emphasis box="[828,847,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[864,958,1825,1851]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="207">caudata</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hendel, F." box="[976,1141,1825,1852]" pageId="12" pageNumber="207" pagination="77 - 117" refId="ref11510" refString="Hendel, F. 1914. Neue Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Pyrgotinen. Archiv fur Naturgeschichte, 79 A (11) (1913), 77 - 117 + 1 Taf." type="journal article" year="1914">Hendel, 1914</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
; these species share elongate and narrow pedicel, elongate and blunt flagellomere 1, small or moderately developed ocellar triangle with 1–2 pairs of ocellar setae, mid and hind coxae of females with more or less thickened setae, and oviscape narrow and long, 1.3–2 times as long as abdominal tergites combined and no sclerotized lobes or long sensillar brushes or combs at its apical aperture. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Enderlein" authorityYear="1942" box="[564,752,1632,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Clemaxia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="angustipalpis">
<emphasis box="[564,583,1632,1658]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[599,752,1632,1658]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">angustipalpis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from superficially 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[174,295,1669,1696]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[174,193,1670,1696]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[213,295,1669,1695]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which shares similarly setulose mid and hind coxae of females, by the long and fine setae of the ventral rows on fore femur (the basalmost seta twice as long as femur width), whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hendel" authorityYear="1914" box="[406,522,1745,1772]" class="Insecta" family="Pyrgotidae" genus="Campylocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[406,425,1745,1771]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[440,522,1745,1771]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="208">gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are short and spurious (the basalmost seta at most as long as femur width).
